04702nam a22007095i 9780801460883DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979577054  a97808014608837 a10.7591/97808014608832doi  a(DE-B1597)478437  a(OCoLC)769190454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPT2603.E455bZ7934 2016 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a838.912092231 aNewman, Jane O., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBenjamin's Library :bModernity, Nation, and the Baroque /cJane O. Newman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (262 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignale: Modern German Letters, Cultures, and Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tTextual Note -- tIntroduction: Benjamin’s Baroque: A Lost Object? -- t1. Inventing the Baroque: A Critical History of Nineteenth- and Early Twentieth-Century Debates -- t2. The Plays Are the Thing: Textual Politics and the German Drama -- t3. Melancholy Germans: War Theology, Allegory, and the Lutheran Baroque -- tConclusion: Baroque Legacies: National Socialism’s Benjamin -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Benjamin's Library, Jane O. Newman offers, for the first time in any language, a reading of Walter Benjamin's notoriously opaque work, Origin of the German Tragic Drama that systematically attends to its place in discussions of the Baroque in Benjamin's day. Taking into account the literary and cultural contexts of Benjamin's work, Newman recovers Benjamin’s relationship to the ideologically loaded readings of the literature and political theory of the seventeenth-century Baroque that abounded in Germany during the political and economic crises of the Weimar years.To date, the significance of the Baroque for Origin of the German Tragic Drama has been glossed over by students of Benjamin, most of whom have neither read it in this context nor engaged with the often incongruous debates about the period that filled both academic and popular texts in the years leading up to and following World War I. Armed with extraordinary historical, bibliographical, philological, and orthographic research, Newman shows the extent to which Benjamin participated in these debates by reconstructing the literal and figurative history of sixteenth- and seventeenth-century books that Benjamin analyzes and the literary, art historical and art theoretical, and political theological discussions of the Baroque with which he was familiar. In so doing, she challenges the exceptionalist, even hagiographic, approaches that have become common in Benjamin studies. The result is a deeply learned book that will infuse much-needed life into the study of one of the most influential thinkers of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBaroque literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aWest European History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801460883zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801460883/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPD